Inauguration of Donald Trump, Donald Trump is inaugurated as the forty-fifth president of the United States
Inauguration of Donald Trump, Donald Trump is inaugurated as the forty-fifth president of the United States
Four million people around the world attend the Women's March protesting the new administration.[13][14] It was the largest single-day protest in U.S. history.
President Trump signs three memoranda. The first withdraws the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership.[27]
Attorney General Sessions recuses himself from any inquiries involving allegations of Russian interference in the 2016 American election

In a House Intelligence Committee hearing, FBI Director James Comey states that their investigation of Russian influence on the presidential election also covers possible links between Russia and Trump campaign figures[295] and that the FBI has no evidence of wiretapping against Trump.

With the consent of President Trump, House Speaker Paul Ryan indefinitely postpones the first major Congressional vote on the repeal and replacement of the Affordable Care Act, due to lack of support from both sides of Congress.
Former National Security Adviser Michael Flynn seeks immunity from the FBI in exchange for testimony on White House links to Russia

House Intelligence Committee Chairman Devin Nunes recuses himself from the investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections and is replaced by Mike Conaway. President Trump orders a strike on the Shayrat Air Base in Homs, Syria, using 59 Tomahawk cruise missiles in retaliation for the chemical weapons attack on April 4. The strike is the first targeted attack by the United States military on the Ba'athist Syrian government forces since the war began.[28] Delivering a statement at Mar-a-Lago, Trump declares an intent to protect American national security by deterring the use of chemical weaponry.
A MOAB bomb is dropped on an ISIS cave complex in Nangarhar Province, Afghanistan; the same province where Staff Sergeant Mark De Alencar of 7th Special Forces Group was killed on April 8

President Trump removes James Comey from his position as FBI Director. The White House explains that it is acting on the recommendation of Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein[153] and Attorney General Jeff Sessions, citing Comey's public statements about the Clinton email investigation as the reason for the decision
